00:20:04,800 --> 00:20:10,397
Mary, Mary
I'm gonna take you out tonight

246
00:20:11,320 --> 00:20:13,390
So hand me down that can o' beans

247
00:20:13,480 --> 00:20:16,836
Hand me down that can o' beans
Hand me down that can o' beans

248
00:20:16,920 --> 00:20:18,956
I'm throwin' it away

249
00:20:19,040 --> 00:20:22,316
Out the window go the beans
Out the window go the beans

250
00:20:22,400 --> 00:20:26,154
Out the window go the beans
Go the beans, go the beans

251
00:20:26,240 --> 00:20:28,879
Good times are here to stay

252
00:20:50,000 --> 00:20:54,676
- Anybody seen Ben Rumson?
- He left here about 20 minutes ago.

253
00:20:54,760 --> 00:20:57,957
- Thanks.
- Are you his pardner?

254
00:20:59,120 --> 00:21:02,999
He owes me $80.
He said you would stand good.

255
00:21:19,640 --> 00:21:21,471
Pardner.

256
00:21:35,000 --> 00:21:38,675
- Can you help me get up on the mule?
- You all right?

257
00:21:40,200 --> 00:21:43,351
I get melancholy every now and then.

258
00:21:43,440 --> 00:21:47,035
It's a disease common to
mountain men who live alone a lot,

259
00:21:47,120 --> 00:21:51,910
but if you stay with me such times,
I'll be OK.

260
00:21:54,080 --> 00:21:55,991
All right.

261
00:22:26,280 --> 00:22:30,239
Did Ezra Atwell come to you
for that $80?

262
00:22:30,720 --> 00:22:33,439
Yeah. I stood good for you.

263
00:22:34,680 --> 00:22:37,752
I guess this is what you meant,
when you said you expected me

264
00:22:37,840 --> 00:22:40,718
to come get you
muddy drunk in the street.

265
00:22:40,800 --> 00:22:44,395
And now you're gonna be my companion
in my moment of despair.

266
00:22:45,440 --> 00:22:51,709
- Well, you're my pardner, ain't you?
- I like you, Pardner.

267
00:22:53,520 --> 00:22:55,476
I like you, Ben.

268
00:23:31,040 --> 00:23:33,349
My mother and father's dead,

269
00:23:35,080 --> 00:23:39,198
and my two brothers and myself,
we worked the farm.

270
00:23:40,280 --> 00:23:44,671
Then last year, my older brother,
he took himself a wife.

271
00:23:44,760 --> 00:23:49,914
Me and my kid brother decided
to leave Michigan and come out here,

272
00:23:50,000 --> 00:23:53,834
maybe dig some gold,
get enough money to buy some land.

273
00:23:54,800 --> 00:23:58,998
Except now that he's gone, I don't
have too much appetite for farming.

274
00:24:00,280 --> 00:24:02,316
What about your girl?

275
00:24:03,520 --> 00:24:06,398
- Girl?
- Yeah. Elisa.

276
00:24:06,480 --> 00:24:10,519
Is she gonna come out and join you,
or did she marry your brother?

277
00:24:12,800 --> 00:24:16,793
To tell you the truth,
there is no Elisa.

278
00:24:17,640 --> 00:24:21,155
I just read that name somewhere
and made it up.

279
00:24:22,240 --> 00:24:27,439
Them's the best kind, but
what I need now is the worst kind.

280
00:24:34,120 --> 00:24:39,319
It's a living hell up here,
what with the bloody rain

281
00:24:39,400 --> 00:24:44,076
and the bloody loneliness,
and that bloody, bloody wind.

282
00:24:45,600 --> 00:24:50,799
Maria, Maria

283
00:24:52,320 --> 00:24:58,714
They call the wind Maria

284
00:25:00,760 --> 00:25:06,710
Away out here they got a name
For rain and wind and fire

285
00:25:06,800 --> 00:25:09,758
The rain is Tess
The fire's Joe

286
00:25:09,840 --> 00:25:14,550
And they call the wind Maria

287
00:25:14,640 --> 00:25:20,954
Maria blows the stars around
And sends the clouds a-flyin'

288
00:25:21,040 --> 00:25:24,350
Maria makes the mountains sound

289
00:25:24,440 --> 00:25:28,558
Like folks were up there dyin'

290
00:25:30,560 --> 00:25:36,795
Maria, Maria

291
00:25:36,880 --> 00:25:42,273
They call the wind Maria

292
00:25:43,760 --> 00:25:49,471
Before I knew Maria's name
And heard her wail and whinin'

293
00:25:49,840 --> 00:25:56,075
I had a girl and she had me
And the sun was always shinin'

294
00:25:58,080 --> 00:26:04,349
But then one day I left my girl
I left her far behind me

295
00:26:04,440 --> 00:26:08,228
And now I'm lost
So goldurn lost

296
00:26:08,320 --> 00:26:13,075
Not even God can find me

297
00:26:14,840 --> 00:26:20,870
Maria, Maria

298
00:26:20,960 --> 00:26:25,954
They call the wind Maria

299
00:26:27,240 --> 00:26:33,429
Out here they got a name for rain
For wind and fire only

300
00:26:33,520 --> 00:26:39,834
But when you're lost and all alone
There ain't no word but lonely

301
00:26:41,480 --> 00:26:47,749
And I'm a lost and lonely man
Without a star to guide me

302
00:26:47,840 --> 00:26:52,118
Maria, blow my love to me

303
00:26:52,200 --> 00:26:57,991
I need my girl beside me

304
00:26:59,040 --> 00:27:03,795
Maria, Maria

305
00:27:05,720 --> 00:27:11,590
They call the wind Maria

306
00:27:11,680 --> 00:27:17,550
Maria, Maria

307
00:27:19,440 --> 00:27:25,310
Blow my love

308
00:27:25,960 --> 00:27:29,270
To me

309
00:27:52,120 --> 00:27:53,348
Women! Look at the women!

310
00:27:54,960 --> 00:27:58,589
Look! Two women!
Look at the two women!

311
00:27:58,680 --> 00:28:02,559
There's five women!
I wanna get one of them gals!

312
00:28:14,360 --> 00:28:16,555
Women! Women!

313
00:28:22,200 --> 00:28:25,909
There's 64 women coming into town!

314
00:28:32,560 --> 00:28:35,358
Men, 80 women coming down the river!

315
00:29:37,440 --> 00:29:41,319
Lady, I got $50 here in gold dust.

316
00:29:42,000 --> 00:29:46,039
You can have it all
if you let me hold the baby.

317
00:29:49,400 --> 00:29:53,234
Very well.
No, I don't want your money for it.

318
00:29:53,320 --> 00:29:56,551
You'll hurt his feelings,
Sarah. Take it.

319
00:30:18,200 --> 00:30:22,079
Look at them eyes,
glowing like he just hit pay dirt.

320
00:30:22,160 --> 00:30:24,355
He's a girl, you bummer!

321
00:30:24,680 --> 00:30:27,035
Would anyone else
care to hold the baby?

322
00:30:27,120 --> 00:30:31,193
- Not now, Jacob.
- Just where are you people from?

323
00:30:31,280 --> 00:30:34,272
Illinois, originally.
I'm Jacob Woodling.

324
00:30:34,360 --> 00:30:39,354
- This is my wife Sarah.
- And who is this fine young lady?

325
00:30:39,440 --> 00:30:42,238
- Her name is Elizabeth Woodling.
- Your sister?

326
00:30:42,320 --> 00:30:44,550
No. My wife.

327
00:30:45,520 --> 00:30:48,478
Your wife?
I thought that one was your wife.

328
00:30:48,560 --> 00:30:52,599
- They both are.
- Holy Moses! They're Mormons!

329
00:30:52,680 --> 00:30:56,036
- Du lieber Himmel!
- Nice work, old man!

330
00:30:58,800 --> 00:31:04,477
- Can we get something to eat there?
- With $50, you can, sir. Follow me.

331
00:31:06,200 --> 00:31:08,395
- What the hell is a Mormons?
- Ich weiß nicht.

332
00:31:47,400 --> 00:31:51,996
Bridegroom,
I don't give a damn how a man prays.

333
00:31:52,080 --> 00:31:56,471
There's room in hell for all of us,
but it just ain't equitable,

334
00:31:56,560 --> 00:32:00,792
for you to be having two of
something all of us got none of.

335
00:32:02,720 --> 00:32:04,631
So I'll tell you what I'm gonna do.

336
00:32:04,720 --> 00:32:10,397
Your mule's lame,
and I got a beauty that cost me $140.

337
00:32:10,480 --> 00:32:14,439
I'll swap you straight,
my mule for one of your wives.

338
00:32:14,520 --> 00:32:17,432
Now, which one's baby's mother?

339
00:32:17,520 --> 00:32:20,956
God knows I wouldn't want
to separate mother and child.

340
00:32:21,040 --> 00:32:24,510
- I am.
- Good. I fancied t'other one, I did.

341
00:32:24,600 --> 00:32:27,398
- This is immoral.
- I hope so!

342
00:32:27,480 --> 00:32:30,711
- The woman's married.
- No, she's not!

343
00:32:30,800 --> 00:32:34,713
We don't recognise plural marriage
in California.

344
00:32:34,800 --> 00:32:38,076
Then I bid $250 in gold for her.

345
00:32:38,160 --> 00:32:40,116
- 260!
- 265!

346
00:32:40,200 --> 00:32:42,794
Wait!
You can't buy a woman for money.

347
00:32:42,880 --> 00:32:44,996
Try and get one without it.

348
00:32:46,720 --> 00:32:49,154
All right, what about it, Mormons?

349
00:32:49,240 --> 00:32:51,629
Jacob, we need every penny,

350
00:32:51,720 --> 00:32:54,871
and I can't bear another day
of those martyred looks.

351
00:32:54,960 --> 00:32:59,431
- There it is again.
- This ain't a martyred look, Sarah.

352
00:32:59,520 --> 00:33:02,398
This look is pure hatred.

353
00:33:03,080 --> 00:33:06,277
Quiet! Brigham Young has 27 wives,

354
00:33:06,360 --> 00:33:09,557
and he hasn't had
half the trouble with them.

355
00:33:09,680 --> 00:33:12,513
Then simplify your life, Jacob.
Sell me.

356
00:33:12,640 --> 00:33:15,871
But, Elizabeth,
you don't know what you'll get.

357
00:33:15,960 --> 00:33:18,633
I know what I've had.

358
00:33:22,840 --> 00:33:25,718
- Go ahead, Jacob.
- Gentlemen...

359
00:33:25,800 --> 00:33:28,872
Out here I ain't a Mormon.

360
00:33:29,440 --> 00:33:31,510
Elizabeth is a headstrong woman,

361
00:33:31,600 --> 00:33:35,354
especially since
her own baby died two weeks ago,

362
00:33:35,440 --> 00:33:37,431
but she's given
her consent to be sold.

363
00:33:37,520 --> 00:33:42,150
Therefore, if any of you
want to bid for her, so be it.

364
00:33:43,240 --> 00:33:47,995
But let's go outside,
where there's room for more people.

365
00:33:48,560 --> 00:33:54,396
But these religious dogs
are bloody greedy! Come on! Come on!

366
00:33:57,480 --> 00:33:59,072
You wait here and feed the baby.

367
00:33:59,160 --> 00:34:01,594
It's not proper
you standing on a block.

368
00:34:01,680 --> 00:34:05,195
If anyone wants to inspect you
I'll send them in.

369
00:34:13,600 --> 00:34:16,751
Order! Order!

370
00:34:17,120 --> 00:34:21,079
I intend to conduct this auction
in an orderly manner!

371
00:34:21,160 --> 00:34:26,837
And no bids in Spanish. The last bid
was $265 and two blankets.

372
00:34:26,920 --> 00:34:30,151
$265, two blankets and a jackass!

373
00:34:30,240 --> 00:34:34,119
A two-pound sack of coffee,
a two-pound sack of brown sugar...

374
00:34:34,200 --> 00:34:38,113
Holbrook, even if she is bought,
how will she marry who bought her?

375
00:34:38,200 --> 00:34:42,113
She'll be married by the
prevailing law of this community,

376
00:34:42,200 --> 00:34:47,911
which is mining law, and she will be
treated like any other legal claim!

377
00:34:49,360 --> 00:34:52,557
Order! Order! Order!

378
00:36:00,040 --> 00:36:04,591
Order! The man bids $275,

379
00:36:04,680 --> 00:36:09,595
four blankets, one pickaxe
and a bedpan.

380
00:36:19,400 --> 00:36:23,279
Mooney, there's a woman in the saloon

381
00:36:23,360 --> 00:36:25,032
with a baby
pressed against her breast.

382
00:36:25,120 --> 00:36:26,519
That's right.

383
00:36:26,600 --> 00:36:30,354
Wait. It ain't every day
that we got a woman in Atwell's

384
00:36:30,440 --> 00:36:33,557
- pressing her breast with her baby.
- That's right.

385
00:36:39,360 --> 00:36:41,351
Clendennon,

386
00:36:41,440 --> 00:36:44,591
there's a woman in Atwell's
pressing her breast to the saloon.

387
00:36:45,680 --> 00:36:47,796
I know, and we're bidding for her.

388
00:36:47,880 --> 00:36:52,078
Sam Fletcher bids $300,
four blankets...

389
00:36:52,160 --> 00:36:53,275
Ben, where you going?

390
00:36:53,360 --> 00:36:57,273
There's a breast in Atwell's
pressing a woman against her.

391
00:36:57,360 --> 00:36:59,874
You better stay here.

392
00:37:03,520 --> 00:37:08,116
- Look! There's another one!
- He's a Mormon. He has two wives.

393
00:37:08,200 --> 00:37:11,192
- I'll kill him.
- They're bidding on her now.

394
00:37:11,280 --> 00:37:16,400
What's the bid?
Whatever the bid is, I double it!

395
00:37:21,800 --> 00:37:24,360
$400 was bid last!

396
00:37:24,440 --> 00:37:30,709
Mr Ben Rumson gallantly
doubles that bid to $800!

397
00:37:32,000 --> 00:37:33,797
800 once...

398
00:37:33,880 --> 00:37:37,190
Wait! I'm his pardner,
and he withdraws the bid.

399
00:37:37,280 --> 00:37:39,874
- You have power of attorney?
- Power of what?

400
00:37:39,960 --> 00:37:42,793
Written permission,
signed and witnessed.

401
00:37:42,880 --> 00:37:45,678
If he could do that,
he'd talk for himself.

402
00:37:45,760 --> 00:37:50,311
- 800 twice!
- Wake up, Ben. Come on.

403
00:37:50,400 --> 00:37:55,633
Sold to Mr Ben Rumson for $800!

404
00:38:59,840 --> 00:39:01,831
He only looks that way
when he's drunk.

405
00:39:01,920 --> 00:39:04,832
You ain't exactly
seein' him at his best,

406
00:39:04,920 --> 00:39:07,673
but once I get him
washed down and clipped,

407
00:39:07,760 --> 00:39:10,718
I think you'll be
agreeably surprised.

408
00:39:12,320 --> 00:39:14,959
Get the soap and water

409
00:39:15,240 --> 00:39:18,198
Get the soap and water

410
00:39:18,280 --> 00:39:21,670
Got a sweet perfumer
To try his humour

411
00:39:21,760 --> 00:39:24,911
It's Ben's weddin' day

412
00:39:25,000 --> 00:39:27,833
Wash him down and clip him

413
00:39:28,120 --> 00:39:31,112
Wash him down and clip him

414
00:39:31,200 --> 00:39:34,715
He's got a blue-eyed wonder
To put him under

415
00:39:34,800 --> 00:39:40,830
It's his weddin', Ben's weddin'
Ben's weddin' day

416
00:39:42,280 --> 00:39:47,434
Where am I goin'?
I don't know

417
00:39:47,520 --> 00:39:53,197
Where am I headin'?
I ain't certain

418
00:39:53,280 --> 00:40:00,391
All I know is I am on my way

419
00:40:00,480 --> 00:40:05,713
Amen

420
00:40:06,720 --> 00:40:08,153
Dearly beloved,

421
00:40:08,240 --> 00:40:11,949
we have gathered together
to grant this man, Ben Rumson,

422
00:40:12,040 --> 00:40:16,192
exclusive title to this woman,
Mrs Elizabeth Woodling,

423
00:40:16,280 --> 00:40:18,919
and to all her mineral resources.

424
00:40:19,000 --> 00:40:21,389
I have drawn up this record of claim,

425
00:40:21,480 --> 00:40:24,392
which here and henceforth
will be recognised

426
00:40:24,480 --> 00:40:26,311
as a certificate of marriage.

427
00:40:26,400 --> 00:40:29,278
So I ask you, Ben,

428
00:40:29,360 --> 00:40:33,148
do you recognise this claim
as a contract of marriage,

429
00:40:33,240 --> 00:40:37,756
and do you take this woman
to love, honour and cherish?

430
00:40:43,120 --> 00:40:45,475
He does.

431
00:40:45,560 --> 00:40:49,633
Elizabeth Woodling,
do you take this man, Ben Rumson,

432
00:40:49,720 --> 00:40:54,032
to love, honour, and obey him
until death do you part?

433
00:40:56,320 --> 00:40:57,673
She does.

434
00:40:57,760 --> 00:41:04,154
I now pronounce you claimed and filed
as Mr and Mrs Ben Rumson.

435
00:41:35,960 --> 00:41:39,873
Mr Rumson went to town
Ridin' on a pony

436
00:41:39,960 --> 00:41:43,714
Bought a wife and brought her home
And called it matrimony

437
00:41:50,520 --> 00:41:54,229
Mr Rumson bought a bride
Out in Californy

438
00:41:54,320 --> 00:41:58,438
He'd have saved a lot of money
Stayin' drunk and horny

439
00:42:08,400 --> 00:42:11,119
Oh, Susannah
He's happy as can be

440
00:42:11,200 --> 00:42:15,034
For he's got him somethin' better
Than a banjo on his knee

441
00:42:21,800 --> 00:42:25,793
Rumson, he got married today
Married today, married today

442
00:42:25,880 --> 00:42:30,192
Rumson, he got married today
What'll he do tomorrow?

443
00:42:35,640 --> 00:42:39,474
Ben! I'll be glad
to help you work your claim!

444
00:43:55,640 --> 00:43:59,315
I'll be bedding down
by the fire if you need me.

445
00:44:11,560 --> 00:44:15,599
You'll not regret taking me in,
I'll make you a good wife.

446
00:44:20,320 --> 00:44:22,390
You sure as hell will.

447
00:44:25,400 --> 00:44:29,598
I don't fault you
for taking me for an easy woman.

448
00:44:29,680 --> 00:44:32,035
I was bought and paid for.

449
00:44:32,120 --> 00:44:35,157
But you bought me for a wife,
not a whore.

450
00:44:36,240 --> 00:44:40,279
If you come again at me again like
a slavering dog, I'll shoot you!

451
00:44:40,360 --> 00:44:42,476
Watch where you point that thing.

452
00:44:42,560 --> 00:44:46,030
You'd blow my manhood
halfway to the moon.

453
00:44:46,120 --> 00:44:50,033
I mean to make you a good wife and
honour this contract of marriage,

454
00:44:50,120 --> 00:44:52,839
but only if you
will honour it as well.

455
00:44:52,920 --> 00:44:54,911
I don't know
what you mean by honour it.

456
00:44:56,640 --> 00:44:59,200
I know your sort of man.

457
00:44:59,280 --> 00:45:04,434
My father was the same sort,
born under a wandering star.

458
00:45:04,520 --> 00:45:08,911
I ain't fool enough to bond you
with all the tyrannies of marriage.

459
00:45:09,000 --> 00:45:11,468
All I want is your name, Mr Rumson,

460
00:45:11,560 --> 00:45:15,678
and the least measure
of respect due to a man's wife.

461
00:45:18,000 --> 00:45:21,231
But most of all,

462
00:45:22,320 --> 00:45:23,878
I want you to build me a cabin.

463
00:45:25,520 --> 00:45:29,877
A cabin that'll stand up
in winter with a fireplace of stone

464
00:45:29,960 --> 00:45:33,191
and a door I can bolt if I have to.

465
00:45:35,640 --> 00:45:39,428
And if you do that, I will say
you have honoured the contract.

466
00:45:41,520 --> 00:45:44,751
But if you regret having bought me,
say so now.

467
00:45:44,840 --> 00:45:49,118
And if I have to work forever,
I'll see you get your $800 back.

468
00:45:51,560 --> 00:45:56,509
I admire your pioneer spirit and
your straightforward manner.

469
00:46:01,520 --> 00:46:05,911
- Is that what you've been admiring?
- I've been admiring you.

470
00:46:09,960 --> 00:46:15,193
All right, I'll build you a cabin,
and I'll give you my name proudly.

471
00:46:16,760 --> 00:46:21,959
You're Mrs Ben Rumson, and I'll kill
any man that says you ain't,

472
00:46:22,040 --> 00:46:25,350
and I'll stick to it till I move on,

473
00:46:25,440 --> 00:46:29,353
which is when the gold pinches out
or the first snow of winter.

474
00:46:36,440 --> 00:46:40,274
You ain't gonna claim duress later
just cos I held a gun on you?

475
00:46:40,360 --> 00:46:44,433
No, ma'am,
I ain't going to claim duress.

476
00:47:03,520 --> 00:47:06,796
I seem to lack
all sense of shame with you.

477
00:47:50,920 --> 00:47:55,311
These men came all the way from
Fiddler's Camp just to see your wife.

478
00:47:55,400 --> 00:47:57,436
Hiya, Ben!

479
00:47:58,000 --> 00:48:02,278
Looks like I married myself
a tourist attraction.

480
00:48:02,360 --> 00:48:06,478
Some of these boys hiked 15 miles.
Ben, how's married life?

481
00:48:07,560 --> 00:48:11,030
Pardner, it was so good,
I forgot that I was married.

482
00:48:30,120 --> 00:48:33,954
I'd hike 15 miles
to look at that myself.

483
00:48:36,040 --> 00:48:38,395
I can see it ain't gonna be easy,

484
00:48:38,480 --> 00:48:41,517
married to the only woman
in these mountains.

485
00:48:56,520 --> 00:49:00,672
All right, boys!
The lady wants a cabin to live in,

486
00:49:00,760 --> 00:49:06,073
a proper cabin made out of wood
that'll hold up in the winter!

487
00:49:06,160 --> 00:49:09,436
So just don't sit there gaping,
get to work!

488
00:49:24,080 --> 00:49:30,030
Send back the world
There's too much night for me

489
00:49:30,120 --> 00:49:35,956
The sky is much too high
To shelter me when darkness falls

490
00:49:37,440 --> 00:49:42,639
Four cabin walls
Would be just right for me

491
00:49:43,560 --> 00:49:46,597
I need a threshold I can cross

492
00:49:46,680 --> 00:49:52,118
Where I can sit
And gather moss forevermore

493
00:49:53,160 --> 00:49:58,837
A million miles away

494
00:49:58,920 --> 00:50:04,040
Behind the door

495
00:50:05,120 --> 00:50:10,797
Roll up the plains
There's too much view for me

496
00:50:11,320 --> 00:50:15,393
There's so much space
Between the waiting heart

497
00:50:15,480 --> 00:50:20,713
And whispered word
It's never heard

498
00:50:22,320 --> 00:50:25,198
One room will do for me

499
00:50:25,280 --> 00:50:29,034
Where every evening
I can stare at someone

500
00:50:29,120 --> 00:50:34,752
Smiling from his chair
Across the floor

501
00:50:35,320 --> 00:50:41,031
A million miles away

502
00:50:41,120 --> 00:50:47,275
Behind the door

503
00:51:08,720 --> 00:51:12,998
Where every evening
I can stare at someone

504
00:51:13,080 --> 00:51:18,552
Smiling from his chair
Across the floor

505
00:51:18,640 --> 00:51:23,714
A million miles away

506
00:51:23,800 --> 00:51:29,033
Behind the door

507
00:51:30,120 --> 00:51:34,750
No fears, no fools

508
00:51:34,840 --> 00:51:39,709
No lies, no rules

509
00:51:39,800 --> 00:51:43,509
Just doing with my life

510
00:51:43,600 --> 00:51:47,354
What life is for

511
00:51:50,200 --> 00:51:54,910
A million miles away

512
00:51:56,880 --> 00:52:02,796
Behind the door

513
00:52:15,400 --> 00:52:17,277
Elizabeth.

514
00:52:20,200 --> 00:52:21,952
Elizabeth?

515
00:52:46,200 --> 00:52:51,991
- Where have you been?
- Down at the rapids taking a bath.

516
00:52:52,080 --> 00:52:55,516
You mean you was taking a bath?

517
00:52:55,600 --> 00:52:58,990
I mean I was taking a bath.
What do you think I mean?

518
00:52:59,080 --> 00:53:05,110
You was down at the rapids just now,
bare beam and buck naked?

519
00:53:05,200 --> 00:53:08,636
I'm not like to take a bath
with my clothes on, Mr Rumson.

520
00:53:08,720 --> 00:53:11,996
Are you trying to tell me
you was taking a bath?

521
00:53:12,080 --> 00:53:17,234
- That's right. I was taking a bath.
- In the middle of the night?

522
00:53:18,320 --> 00:53:24,589
Mr Rumson, in a community of 400 men,
would you rather I took my bath

523
00:53:24,680 --> 00:53:29,276
bare beam and buck naked
in the middle of the day?

524
00:53:35,360 --> 00:53:38,397
- What's the matter with you?
- What's the matter with me?

525
00:53:39,880 --> 00:53:43,998
I ain't running around in the
middle of the night in my drawers.

526
00:54:01,800 --> 00:54:05,190
Hey, boys! Listen to this.

527
00:54:05,280 --> 00:54:09,592
"The proprietors of the
Hares and Hounds Club in Sonora

528
00:54:09,680 --> 00:54:14,595
"wish to announce that six ladies
are expected to arrive by stage

529
00:54:14,680 --> 00:54:18,309
"from San Francisco
on the 15th of August".

530
00:54:19,480 --> 00:54:23,109
- How about that.
- That's a hundred miles away.

531
00:54:23,200 --> 00:54:25,236
What good is that gonna do us?

532
00:54:25,320 --> 00:54:28,710
Ain't no one trying
to steal your wife, Ben.

533
00:54:28,800 --> 00:54:31,951
I'll admit there's a few
who wouldn't mind trying.

534
00:54:32,040 --> 00:54:35,749
Horace Tabor, for instance.
He likes to give her a look.

535
00:54:35,840 --> 00:54:39,674
- Horace Tabor?
- Come on, Ben.

536
00:54:39,760 --> 00:54:43,230
He just looks. She doesn't
encourage him or anybody else.

537
00:54:43,320 --> 00:54:46,551
But you're beginning
to cut a comical figure.

538
00:54:46,640 --> 00:54:50,997
- Everybody's laughing at you.
- I would've never thought of Tabor.

539
00:55:03,200 --> 00:55:06,476
What the hell are you looking at,
Horace Tabor?

540
00:55:07,160 --> 00:55:09,355
I'm looking for my stirring stick.

541
00:55:09,440 --> 00:55:11,715
You make any more
advances towards my wife,

542
00:55:11,800 --> 00:55:15,554
and I'm gonna shoot you down
like the dog you are!

543
00:55:15,640 --> 00:55:19,872
And the rest of you horny gorillas!
You want something to do?

544
00:55:19,960 --> 00:55:24,590
Put up your money for them six
French tarts coming into Sonora!

545
00:55:24,680 --> 00:55:27,877
But keep your lusting minds
off of my wife!

546
00:55:27,960 --> 00:55:33,956
I'd advise you, Rumson,
not to refer to me as a dog again.

547
00:55:34,120 --> 00:55:37,715
- Is that clear?
- I'll stick my fist in your ear!

548
00:55:37,800 --> 00:55:41,031
- Why you...!
- Grab Tabor! Stop him!

549
00:55:41,120 --> 00:55:43,156
Get back! Get ahold of him!

550
00:55:44,320 --> 00:55:46,151
Mr Rumson!

551
00:55:46,240 --> 00:55:49,198
- Rumson, I...
- Mr Rumson!

552
00:55:49,280 --> 00:55:51,953
Nobody has behaved unseemly to me.

553
00:55:52,040 --> 00:55:55,237
I have been treated with nothing
but kindness in this camp,

554
00:55:55,320 --> 00:56:00,838
and you owe every one of these men,
especially Mr Tabor, an apology.

555
00:56:05,000 --> 00:56:07,195
By God, you're right!

556
00:56:08,120 --> 00:56:12,398
I don't know what's come over me.
I've been behaving like a damn fool,

557
00:56:12,480 --> 00:56:17,395
and I wish to beg your communal
pardons, especially yours,

558
00:56:17,480 --> 00:56:19,198
Horace Tabor.

559
00:56:19,280 --> 00:56:22,909
I suppose if I was married
to the only woman

560
00:56:23,000 --> 00:56:26,595
in the neighbourhood,
I might be just as demented.

561
00:56:28,200 --> 00:56:32,716
And, Mrs Rumson!
May I extend my compliments?

562
00:56:32,800 --> 00:56:35,109
You are as wise as you are fair.

563
00:56:37,120 --> 00:56:40,476
- Get your hands off!
- That lunatic tried to kill me!

564
00:56:41,600 --> 00:56:47,152
I demand a town meeting to consider
a proper course of action.

565
00:56:49,240 --> 00:56:54,712
If that knife had come one inch
lower, I would not be here today.

566
00:56:54,800 --> 00:56:58,156
- That's right.
- Fellow citizens,

567
00:56:58,240 --> 00:57:03,997
as long as that madman
prowls among us, no one is safe.

568
00:57:04,080 --> 00:57:08,756
Therefore, we must
find a solution by tonight.

569
00:57:08,840 --> 00:57:14,631
Let us not wait until the condition
worsens or his aim improves!

570
00:57:15,120 --> 00:57:17,031
- Thank you.
- Order!

571
00:57:17,120 --> 00:57:22,399
- Mr Chairman!
- The chair recognises Ezra Atwell.

572
00:57:24,520 --> 00:57:27,592
I would like
to ask Ben Rumson directly

573
00:57:27,680 --> 00:57:30,877
if he doesn't think
that with a little sober effort

574
00:57:30,960 --> 00:57:33,269
he could control
these fits of jealousy?

575
00:57:33,360 --> 00:57:36,750
No. It's getting worse every day.
Sorry, I can't help you.

576
00:57:36,840 --> 00:57:41,516
- The chair recognises Ben's pardner.
- Thank you, Mr Holbrook.

577
00:57:41,600 --> 00:57:45,149
I've been giving it
some considerable thought,

578
00:57:45,240 --> 00:57:48,949
ever since Ben Rumson,
my pardner here, poor bastard...

579
00:57:49,040 --> 00:57:54,034
Excuse me, ma'am...
Well, ever since he became a lunatic.

580
00:57:55,200 --> 00:57:58,237
What's putting the strain
on Ben's mind

581
00:57:58,320 --> 00:58:01,357
<b>is having the only woman
for 90 miles around here.</b>

582
00:58:01,440 --> 00:58:05,752
My proposal is that we
get some more women for this town.

583
00:58:06,840 --> 00:58:09,354
How you gonna get women
to come up here?

584
00:58:09,440 --> 00:58:13,831
- Order! Order!
- I know where we can get some women.

585
00:58:13,920 --> 00:58:17,151
The six French bawds arriving
in Sonora a week Saturday.

586
00:58:17,240 --> 00:58:18,275
You're right.

587
00:58:18,360 --> 00:58:20,555
Let's get them
to come up here instead.

588
00:58:20,640 --> 00:58:24,713
How? If I was a French bawd,
I'd go to Sonora.

589
00:58:24,800 --> 00:58:27,439
If you was a French bawd,
we'd have no trouble.

590
00:58:27,520 --> 00:58:29,715
How will we get 'em up here?

591
00:58:29,800 --> 00:58:32,598
They gotta take the stage
from Sacramento,

592
00:58:32,680 --> 00:58:35,353
and change horses
at Starbottle's Pass.

593
00:58:35,440 --> 00:58:38,796
So five of us go down there,
hijack that stage,

594
00:58:38,880 --> 00:58:42,953
re-route them tarts up here instead.
What's so hard about that?

595
00:58:44,040 --> 00:58:46,110
It all sounds just fine to me.

596
00:58:46,200 --> 00:58:49,590
- When do we go?!
- Order! Order!

597
00:58:49,680 --> 00:58:51,955
Is it your proposal, Mr Rumson,

598
00:58:52,040 --> 00:58:57,831
that we knock out the stage driver,
steal a coach and kidnap six women?

599
00:58:57,920 --> 00:58:59,751
Sounds better every time I hear it.

600
00:58:59,840 --> 00:59:03,628
- You don't see what's wrong with it?
- What?

601
00:59:03,720 --> 00:59:07,110
If you don't consider
assault and battery,

602
00:59:07,200 --> 00:59:12,069
grand larceny and kidnapping wrong,
what the hell do you consider wrong?

603
00:59:12,160 --> 00:59:14,310
- You maniac!
- Sit down!

604
00:59:14,400 --> 00:59:18,871
- You insane man!
- Schermerhorn, you're out of order.

605
00:59:18,960 --> 00:59:21,554
- What?
- I yield the floor.

606
00:59:21,640 --> 00:59:24,279
- Proceed, Schermerhorn.
- What?

607
00:59:24,360 --> 00:59:28,990
- Speak!
- You maniac! You insane man!

608
00:59:29,080 --> 00:59:31,958
What do you think them people
in Sonora will do

609
00:59:32,040 --> 00:59:34,759
<b>when we hijack their Fräuleins?</b>

610
00:59:34,840 --> 00:59:39,789
They grab their guns
and come up here to get them back!

611
00:59:43,720 --> 00:59:45,438
Order, order!

612
00:59:45,520 --> 00:59:48,671
- Gentlemen!
- Mr Atwell has the floor.

613
00:59:49,760 --> 00:59:53,036
Gentlemen, it is 50 miles
from here to Starbottle's

614
00:59:53,120 --> 00:59:57,079
without a road or a trail.
Not even my mule can do it, how...

615
00:59:57,160 --> 01:00:01,915
You lunatics!
Besides a civil war with Sonora,

616
01:00:02,000 --> 01:00:06,232
you want to put us
in the white slave business!

617
01:00:06,320 --> 01:00:08,914
Schermerhorn, you're out of order!

618
01:00:10,080 --> 01:00:12,753
- Again?
- You haven't been recognised!

619
01:00:13,280 --> 01:00:15,032
I'm Schermerhorn.

620
01:00:15,120 --> 01:00:17,588
- Mr Holbrook.
- Oh, sit down!

621
01:00:17,680 --> 01:00:22,390
Ben, these boys are right.
Mr Holbrook, I withdraw the proposal.

622
01:00:23,280 --> 01:00:25,635
Have you gone out of your skull?

623
01:00:25,720 --> 01:00:28,996
You can't expect them
to build a two-storey building

624
01:00:29,080 --> 01:00:31,992
- just to get women here.
- Who said two storeys?

625
01:00:32,080 --> 01:00:34,753
Somebody has to run the faro tables.

626
01:00:34,840 --> 01:00:36,796
Rotten Luck Willie will.

627
01:00:36,880 --> 01:00:41,431
You can't expect him to build a fancy
building with chandeliers

628
01:00:41,520 --> 01:00:46,469
and masterpieces of art and gambling,
and six beautiful tarts upstairs.

629
01:00:46,560 --> 01:00:50,758
We'd have every bummer for miles
around coming here to spend his money

630
01:00:50,840 --> 01:00:54,196
on women and whisky
at Atwell's and Schermerhorn's.

631
01:00:54,280 --> 01:00:56,236
You think that's bad?

632
01:00:59,080 --> 01:01:02,675
Why, it's terrible! Just terrible!

633
01:01:02,760 --> 01:01:07,038
You'd turn this camp into a boom
town! We don't want to do that.

634
01:01:07,120 --> 01:01:10,476
- Soon there'd be another saloon.
- And a bawdy house!

635
01:01:10,560 --> 01:01:14,109
- And another gambling hall!
- And another bawdy house!

636
01:01:14,200 --> 01:01:16,919
- And hotels!
- Property would shoot straight up.

637
01:01:17,000 --> 01:01:20,709
They'd make more money
selling old claims than gold.

638
01:01:20,800 --> 01:01:24,190
These men didn't come
out here to forge a nation!

639
01:01:24,280 --> 01:01:28,751
That's for men with a big dream,
with visions of America's greatness.

640
01:01:28,840 --> 01:01:34,756
I'm warning you, if you want to turn
us into a dreary boom town metropolis

641
01:01:34,840 --> 01:01:36,796
filled with nothing but millionaires,

642
01:01:36,880 --> 01:01:43,274
all you gotta do is put up one
little, tiny two-storey cathouse!

643
01:01:43,880 --> 01:01:48,192
I say let's put it to a vote,
and any man opposed is a traitor!

644
01:01:48,280 --> 01:01:53,912
All those in favour of bringing
prostitution to this camp, say aye!

645
01:01:59,480 --> 01:02:00,674
Passed!

646
01:02:02,960 --> 01:02:07,795
There's a shifty side to you that
I'm just beginning to appreciate.

647
01:02:08,880 --> 01:02:12,190
- Why can't I go along with you?
- Who'll take care of Elizabeth?

648
01:02:12,280 --> 01:02:15,556
Lt'll take three days
to get them tarts back here.

649
01:02:15,640 --> 01:02:19,633
You don't expect me to leave her
alone in the middle of this?

650
01:02:19,720 --> 01:02:21,790
Who can I trust if it ain't you?

651
01:02:22,400 --> 01:02:25,358
You didn't say being pardners
meant wife-guarding.

652
01:02:25,440 --> 01:02:27,635
Well, it just come up.

653
01:03:02,840 --> 01:03:05,308
- Howdy.
- Captain Barnsfeather, Fort Sumter.

654
01:03:05,400 --> 01:03:09,951
- When does the Sonora stage come?
- About four o'clock tomorrow. Why?

655
01:03:11,040 --> 01:03:14,237
Supplies for the troops. Unmount!

656
01:03:50,640 --> 01:03:52,437
Come in, Pardner.

657
01:03:58,040 --> 01:04:01,794
- You sure I'm not intruding?
- Come in.

658
01:04:06,400 --> 01:04:09,631
Will Ben really
get back in three days?

659
01:04:09,720 --> 01:04:12,598
- Why?
- I'd like to know.

660
01:04:13,440 --> 01:04:15,396
Who you expecting for dinner?

661
01:04:16,880 --> 01:04:19,394
You! Sit down.

662
01:04:21,800 --> 01:04:23,597
Thanks.

663
01:04:27,480 --> 01:04:30,074
I didn't know you was expecting me.

664
01:05:28,240 --> 01:05:32,552
I talk to the trees

665
01:05:32,640 --> 01:05:36,713
But they don't listen to me

666
01:05:37,360 --> 01:05:40,830
I talk to the stars

667
01:05:40,920 --> 01:05:45,277
But they never hear me

668
01:05:45,960 --> 01:05:50,351
The breeze hasn't time

669
01:05:50,440 --> 01:05:54,115
To stop and hear what I say

670
01:05:55,000 --> 01:05:58,037
I talk to them all

671
01:05:59,360 --> 01:06:02,397
In vain

672
01:06:04,400 --> 01:06:06,994
But suddenly my words

673
01:06:07,080 --> 01:06:12,234
Reach someone else's ear

674
01:06:12,320 --> 01:06:19,032
Touch someone else's
heartstrings too

675
01:06:21,720 --> 01:06:25,998
I tell you my dreams

676
01:06:26,640 --> 01:06:30,235
And while you're listening to me

677
01:06:31,720 --> 01:06:37,511
I suddenly see them
Come true

678
01:06:39,040 --> 01:06:43,477
I can see us on an April night

679
01:06:43,560 --> 01:06:47,599
Looking out across a rollin' farm

680
01:06:47,680 --> 01:06:51,878
Having supper in the candlelight

681
01:06:51,960 --> 01:06:56,829
Walkin' later arm in arm

682
01:06:56,920 --> 01:07:01,152
Then I'll tell you
how I passed the day

683
01:07:01,240 --> 01:07:05,233
Thinking mainly
how the night would be

684
01:07:05,320 --> 01:07:09,552
Then I'll try to find
the words to say

685
01:07:09,640 --> 01:07:14,270
All the things you mean to me

686
01:07:15,200 --> 01:07:19,910
I tell you my dreams

687
01:07:20,480 --> 01:07:24,314
And while you're listening to me

688
01:07:25,400 --> 01:07:29,393
I suddenly see them

689
01:07:30,840 --> 01:07:36,312
Come true

690
01:07:37,920 --> 01:07:39,069
They're coming out of Starbottle's!

691
01:07:41,360 --> 01:07:43,828
All right! Fall together!

692
01:07:43,920 --> 01:07:46,639
Put me down, you bloody idiot!
Put me down!

693
01:07:46,720 --> 01:07:51,919
- Down, down, down, down!
- Get in line!

694
01:07:55,440 --> 01:07:57,271
Come on, move!

695
01:08:09,640 --> 01:08:13,394
Captain Barnsfeather, Fort Sumter.
At your service, ladies.

696
01:08:13,480 --> 01:08:19,032
Here to protect you along the way!
We're gonna have to take this detour.

697
01:08:19,120 --> 01:08:24,274
- A detour through open country?
- The road up ahead ain't safe.

698
01:08:24,360 --> 01:08:27,636
- Injuns!
- Ain't no Injuns around here!

699
01:08:30,040 --> 01:08:32,076
Get back in the coach, ladies.

700
01:08:58,800 --> 01:09:02,873
- There's a coach comin' in!
- Comin' in!

701
01:09:04,880 --> 01:09:08,190
There's a coach comin' in
If you listen, you can hear it

702
01:09:08,280 --> 01:09:11,590
A-clip-cloppin' over the hill

703
01:09:11,680 --> 01:09:14,956
And the sound that you hear
Is as good to your ear

704
01:09:15,040 --> 01:09:18,350
As the call of
the wild whippoorwill

705
01:09:18,440 --> 01:09:21,910
There's a coach comin' in
You can feel it gettin' near

706
01:09:22,000 --> 01:09:25,231
All at once
And it bursts into view

707
01:09:25,320 --> 01:09:28,995
And it looks to your eye
Like it fell from the sky

708
01:09:29,080 --> 01:09:31,913
Like a coach
Full of dreams come true

709
01:09:32,000 --> 01:09:35,595
For it's bringin' me
Eyes that are moonlight

710
01:09:35,680 --> 01:09:39,195
And it's carryin' lips
That are wine

711
01:09:39,280 --> 01:09:42,397
And it's comin'
With arms that are pillows

712
01:09:42,480 --> 01:09:45,995
And this evening
It all will be mine

713
01:09:46,080 --> 01:09:49,390
There's a coach comin' in
And you're smellin' like a steer

714
01:09:49,480 --> 01:09:52,756
Get the soap out
It ain't far away

715
01:09:52,840 --> 01:09:56,355
Cut the socks from your feet

716
01:09:56,440 --> 01:09:59,750
Rake your hair till it's neat

717
01:09:59,840 --> 01:10:04,914
There's a coach comin' in
There's a coach comin' in today

718
01:10:05,000 --> 01:10:08,470
There's a coach comin' in
Hurry, hurry, do you hear?

719
01:10:08,560 --> 01:10:11,677
With a cargo o' joy from Paree

720
01:10:11,760 --> 01:10:15,196
Drop the tables and chairs
Get them beds up the stairs

721
01:10:15,280 --> 01:10:18,989
And be sure
Every lock has a key

722
01:10:32,560 --> 01:10:35,791
For it's coming with girls
Who buy perfume

723
01:10:35,880 --> 01:10:39,475
Who wear powder
And rouge from Paree

724
01:10:39,560 --> 01:10:42,711
Who will have to go
Somewhere to get them

725
01:10:42,800 --> 01:10:46,076
And the somewhere to go will be me

726
01:10:46,160 --> 01:10:49,630
There's a coach comin' in
And it's flyin' like a deer

727
01:10:49,720 --> 01:10:52,951
Thank the Lord
There's relief on the way

728
01:10:53,040 --> 01:10:56,749
Thank with all of your hearts

729
01:10:56,840 --> 01:11:00,037
For them half-dozen tarts

730
01:11:00,120 --> 01:11:04,477
There's a coach comin' in today

731
01:11:05,240 --> 01:11:08,710
There's a coach comin' in
If you listen you can hear it

732
01:11:08,800 --> 01:11:11,951
A-clip-cloppin' over the hill

733
01:11:12,040 --> 01:11:15,715
And the sound that you hear
Is as good to your ear

734
01:11:15,800 --> 01:11:19,429
As the call
Of a wild whippoorwill

735
01:11:32,680 --> 01:11:36,150
For it's bringin' me eyes
That are moonlight

736
01:11:36,240 --> 01:11:40,074
And it's carryin' lips
That are wine

737
01:11:40,160 --> 01:11:43,436
And it's comin' with arms
That are pillows

738
01:11:43,520 --> 01:11:46,717
And this evening
It all will be mine

739
01:12:19,400 --> 01:12:23,109
There's a coach comin' in
You can feel it gettin' near

740
01:12:23,200 --> 01:12:26,476
All at once
And it bursts into view

741
01:12:26,560 --> 01:12:29,791
And it looks to your eye
Like it fell from the sky

742
01:12:29,880 --> 01:12:33,429
Like a coach
Full of dreams come true

743
01:12:33,520 --> 01:12:36,830
For it's bringin' me
Eyes that are moonlight

744
01:12:36,920 --> 01:12:40,117
And it's carryin' lips
That are wine

745
01:12:40,200 --> 01:12:43,556
And it's comin'
With arms that are pillows

746
01:12:43,640 --> 01:12:47,076
And this evening
It all will be mine

747
01:12:47,160 --> 01:12:50,755
There's a coach comin' in
Now it's riding in the clear

748
01:12:50,840 --> 01:12:54,276
And the sound of it grows to a din

749
01:12:54,360 --> 01:12:59,912
No, there ain't far to go
Now they're hollerin' "whoa!"

750
01:13:01,080 --> 01:13:03,878
There's a coach comin' in
There's a coach comin'

751
01:13:03,960 --> 01:13:06,235
And it's here

752
01:14:22,080 --> 01:14:23,877
Ben!

753
01:14:27,640 --> 01:14:29,392
Pardner, I wanna talk to you!

754
01:14:32,960 --> 01:14:36,396
You rotten, lecherous,
deceiving, no-good, thieving...

755
01:14:36,480 --> 01:14:40,155
The only reason I ain't blowing
your brains out is the relief

756
01:14:40,240 --> 01:14:44,518
it's gonna give me when
I tear you apart with my bare hands.

757
01:14:44,600 --> 01:14:46,238
What's the matter with you?

758
01:14:46,320 --> 01:14:49,756
What was the two of you
doing on the same horse?

759
01:14:49,840 --> 01:14:52,957
Riding. What else?
That's the last place I'd...

760
01:14:53,040 --> 01:14:56,555
- Where was her horse?
- That was her horse.

761
01:14:56,640 --> 01:15:00,155
And where was your horse?

762
01:15:01,280 --> 01:15:03,111
You had my horse.

763
01:15:10,160 --> 01:15:13,277
If that's true,
why ain't you fighting back?

764
01:15:13,360 --> 01:15:15,430
Cos you ain't been yourself lately.

765
01:15:15,520 --> 01:15:19,672
That's a widely known fact,
and you know it yourself.

766
01:15:21,040 --> 01:15:23,156
Get up, Pardner.

767
01:15:28,880 --> 01:15:32,589
- How's your jaw?
- Feels like it's coming off.

768
01:15:33,960 --> 01:15:38,397
- You ought to trust me, Ben.
- You're right.

769
01:15:38,480 --> 01:15:42,837
You ain't the kind of man that'd go
lusting after another man's wife,

770
01:15:42,920 --> 01:15:46,230
especially with them six bawds
arriving in town.

771
01:15:46,320 --> 01:15:49,756
That's right, Ben.
I wouldn't do that.

772
01:15:50,560 --> 01:15:55,076
The only kind of feelings
you'd ever have would be deep ones,

773
01:15:55,160 --> 01:15:57,116
and if you had 'em for Elizabeth,

774
01:15:57,200 --> 01:16:00,556
you'd come and tell me
before you would her.

775
01:16:01,640 --> 01:16:04,234
That's right, Ben.
That's what I'd do.

776
01:16:05,320 --> 01:16:09,108
- You're a good man, Pardner.
- That's what I was coming to do.

777
01:16:09,200 --> 01:16:12,272
Tell you I got
some deep feelings for Elizabeth.

778
01:16:16,800 --> 01:16:19,872
You hit me one more time,
I'll bust your skull open.

779
01:16:19,960 --> 01:16:25,353
Nothing's happened, and nothing's
gonna happen, cos I'm leaving.

780
01:16:28,000 --> 01:16:29,911
You're breaking up the partnership?

781
01:16:31,280 --> 01:16:35,273
If I hang around here long enough
watching you and her together,

782
01:16:35,360 --> 01:16:38,318
I'll become
as big a lunatic as you are.

783
01:16:43,720 --> 01:16:45,472
All right.

784
01:16:47,040 --> 01:16:50,191
I'll go get your share
of the gold dust.

785
01:16:56,280 --> 01:16:59,829
You can have the mule
and that new gold pan.

786
01:17:01,920 --> 01:17:05,310
You can even have the rocker,
if you want to.

787
01:17:13,440 --> 01:17:17,149
What's the matter, Ben?
Where you taking the rocker?

788
01:17:17,240 --> 01:17:19,834
It's for Pardner. He's going away.

789
01:17:21,520 --> 01:17:26,116
Going away?
He never mentioned going away to me.

790
01:17:27,280 --> 01:17:31,353
Of course not. You don't know
that man like I do, Elizabeth.

791
01:17:32,040 --> 01:17:33,792
What are you saying?

792
01:17:36,400 --> 01:17:38,960
He loves you. That's why he's going.

793
01:17:40,600 --> 01:17:44,275
I don't want Pardner to go.
I love him.

794
01:17:53,880 --> 01:17:58,954
Unpack, Pardner. You ain't going
nowhere. That woman loves you.

795
01:18:04,400 --> 01:18:08,029
And that puts a new wheel
on the wagon, don't it?

796
01:18:09,040 --> 01:18:13,670
Get this straight. I'm not taking
away your wife, and that's final.

797
01:18:13,760 --> 01:18:17,389
- But you love her.
- So do you.

798
01:18:18,840 --> 01:18:22,469
There's only one way for anybody
to be happy and that's...

799
01:18:22,560 --> 01:18:26,519
for one of us to move away
and forget it. And I'm going.

800
01:18:28,520 --> 01:18:30,351
Get out of my way.

801
01:18:37,280 --> 01:18:40,909
Pardner, there comes a time
in the life of every partnership

802
01:18:41,000 --> 01:18:44,515
when the party of the first part
has no recourse

803
01:18:44,600 --> 01:18:48,798
except to knock some sense
into the party of the second part!

804
01:18:48,880 --> 01:18:50,677
You're staying!

805
01:19:15,280 --> 01:19:19,034
- What happened?
- He's staying.

806
01:19:23,320 --> 01:19:26,835
- Is he hurt?
- No. Just tired.

807
01:19:26,920 --> 01:19:30,310
He'll be good as new
in a couple of weeks.

808
01:19:36,800 --> 01:19:38,756
Where you going, Ben?

809
01:19:38,840 --> 01:19:43,868
You love Pardner? You take him.
And you take good care of him.

810
01:19:43,960 --> 01:19:48,590
That's the decentest man
I ever run across. And the strongest.

811
01:19:51,120 --> 01:19:56,353
Now, I know you women like
things legal, so here's what.

812
01:19:56,440 --> 01:20:00,115
It takes two weeks for you
to be an abandoned claim.

813
01:20:00,200 --> 01:20:04,432
After that, you take the name
of your new owner

814
01:20:04,520 --> 01:20:08,354
and file it down
at the mining office.

815
01:20:08,440 --> 01:20:10,908
Then everything'll be legal.

816
01:20:16,720 --> 01:20:19,917
I don't want you to go.
I love you.

817
01:20:21,880 --> 01:20:23,916
What are you talking about?

818
01:20:26,440 --> 01:20:29,432
You're my husband.
I don't want you to go away.

819
01:20:29,520 --> 01:20:33,149
- What was that?
- Don't let him go, Pardner.

820
01:20:36,720 --> 01:20:40,679
- You said she was in love with me.
- Didn't you say you loved him?

821
01:20:40,760 --> 01:20:43,149
Yes, I did, and I do.

822
01:20:43,240 --> 01:20:45,435
You just said
you were in love with Ben.

823
01:20:45,520 --> 01:20:47,351
Yes, I did, and I am.

824
01:20:50,640 --> 01:20:54,599
Ben, do you get that feeling
you need a drink?

825
01:20:54,680 --> 01:20:58,389
- How did you know?
- Cos I do, too.

826
01:20:59,440 --> 01:21:02,637
- But, Pardner, you don't drink.
- No, but I'm changing.

827
01:21:04,680 --> 01:21:06,910
And it takes a woman to do it.

828
01:21:07,440 --> 01:21:09,635
Bless their hearts.

829
01:21:18,040 --> 01:21:23,068
Now, Elizabeth, let's try
and be reasonable about this.

830
01:21:24,160 --> 01:21:26,674
For God's sake, make up your mind!

831
01:21:27,800 --> 01:21:32,316
I can't. I love both of you.

832
01:21:32,400 --> 01:21:36,359
But that ain't going to work.
You can't have both of us.

833
01:21:37,440 --> 01:21:39,954
- Why not?
- Why not?

834
01:21:40,040 --> 01:21:45,592
- Why not?
- A woman can't have two husbands.

835
01:21:47,320 --> 01:21:50,357
I was married
to a man who had two wives.

836
01:21:50,440 --> 01:21:53,000
Why can't a woman have two husbands?

837
01:21:53,080 --> 01:21:57,790
- Because you can't.
- Well, why?

838
01:21:59,080 --> 01:22:03,039
- You explain it to her, Ben.
- I'd like to oblige, Pardner,

839
01:22:03,120 --> 01:22:06,874
but I'll be damned
if I can think of a reason.

840
01:22:06,960 --> 01:22:10,509
Out here we make up
our own rules as we go along.

841
01:22:10,600 --> 01:22:15,628
A man with two wives wants to sell
one at auction, nobody thinks twice.

842
01:22:15,720 --> 01:22:20,794
If a town needs females, hijacking
'em seems the natural thing to do.

843
01:22:20,880 --> 01:22:23,678
And if two pardners
want to share a wife, why not?

844
01:22:23,760 --> 01:22:27,275
This ain't Michigan.
It's gold country.

845
01:22:27,360 --> 01:22:29,635
Why, hell, it's the golden country!

846
01:22:29,720 --> 01:22:32,837
Untouched and uncontaminated
by human hands!

847
01:22:32,920 --> 01:22:36,196
People can look civilisation
in the eye and spit!

848
01:22:36,280 --> 01:22:40,592
You don't have to please anybody,
don't have to love thy neighbour.

849
01:22:40,680 --> 01:22:43,478
It's wild, human and free,

850
01:22:43,560 --> 01:22:47,394
and all over this nation,
they preach against it every Sunday.

851
01:22:47,480 --> 01:22:50,153
But I don't think God's listening.
You know why?

852
01:22:50,240 --> 01:22:53,869
Because he's here,
in glorious California!

853
01:22:55,200 --> 01:22:59,671
- You trying to say you're willing?
- I am.

854
01:22:59,760 --> 01:23:05,153
I think it's a humane,
practical, beautiful solution.

855
01:23:05,240 --> 01:23:08,118
- It does make a lot of sense.
- It don't.

856
01:23:08,200 --> 01:23:11,272
It don't in Michigan.
It does in California.

857
01:23:11,360 --> 01:23:14,670
- What's everybody gonna say?
- Who are you talking about?

858
01:23:14,760 --> 01:23:18,878
You mean everybody in town
playing them French horns?

859
01:23:18,960 --> 01:23:22,111
They'd be damn glad
to have two less in line.

860
01:23:31,000 --> 01:23:32,831
You're right.

861
01:23:32,920 --> 01:23:37,038
Of course I'm right. It's not like
somebody was asking you

862
01:23:37,120 --> 01:23:40,078
to do something immoral,
like stealing gold!

863
01:23:40,160 --> 01:23:43,516
- It ain't as bad as all that.
- What the hell's bad about it?

864
01:23:43,600 --> 01:23:45,352
Show me on that list of commandments

865
01:23:45,440 --> 01:23:48,830
where it says a woman
can't have two husbands.

866
01:23:48,920 --> 01:23:51,309
There ain't no commandment like that!

867
01:23:53,600 --> 01:23:57,479
Hot damn! I think it's great!
It's history-making!

868
01:24:06,720 --> 01:24:08,676
Can't hold it.

869
01:24:12,880 --> 01:24:15,997
- Elizabeth?
- Yes, Ben?

870
01:24:16,080 --> 01:24:18,469
We will be three for dinner.

871
01:29:08,120 --> 01:29:09,872
Shameless harlots!

872
01:29:09,960 --> 01:29:14,750
You think the Lord was some boy in
a raggedy old sheet 2,000 years ago?

873
01:29:14,840 --> 01:29:18,594
You're wrong.
He's here now and he sees you!

874
01:29:25,400 --> 01:29:31,270
Ye godless jaspers! Who are you?
Freemasons? Rosicrucians?

875
01:29:31,480 --> 01:29:34,836
Heathen emissaries
from the dens of Babylon?

876
01:29:34,920 --> 01:29:37,115
Boozers. Gluttons.

877
01:29:37,200 --> 01:29:41,512
Gamblers. Harlots. Fornicators!

878
01:29:43,640 --> 01:29:48,634
- What's a fornicator?
- I don't know. I ain't religious.

879
01:29:54,560 --> 01:29:59,509
The stench of the city is in the
Lord's nostrils, making Him sick.

880
01:29:59,600 --> 01:30:02,433
The Lord ain't gonna take it
much longer!

881
01:30:02,520 --> 01:30:06,593
Come on up, Parson,
and get some old-time religion.

882
01:30:14,040 --> 01:30:18,477
- Mrs Rumson. How are your husbands?
- Fine. Thank you, Mr Atwell.

883
01:30:18,560 --> 01:30:21,916
Husbands? Did I hear husbands?

884
01:30:22,000 --> 01:30:25,834
You animals! You pagans!

885
01:30:27,520 --> 01:30:32,878
O God, Lord of hosts,
close thine eyes, then hold thy nose.

886
01:30:32,960 --> 01:30:36,236
I am passing through
the garbage of humanity!

887
01:30:36,320 --> 01:30:38,276
Come on, dearie.

888
01:30:38,360 --> 01:30:42,751
Scum, keep your filthy claws
off my wife, Princess Hummingbird!

889
01:30:44,240 --> 01:30:46,470
You heathen swine!

890
01:30:46,560 --> 01:30:49,518
Do you know what God done
to Sodom and Gomorrah

891
01:30:49,600 --> 01:30:53,479
when he couldn't find 50 righteous
men in them stinking cities?

892
01:30:55,200 --> 01:30:57,839
I'll show God a place
where there ain't 40.

893
01:30:57,920 --> 01:30:59,876
- Yeah!
- 30!

894
01:30:59,960 --> 01:31:02,076
- Yeah!
- Two!

895
01:31:02,160 --> 01:31:04,833
- Yeah!
- Or one!

896
01:31:04,920 --> 01:31:08,913
- Yeah!
- And here it is.

897
01:31:09,200 --> 01:31:13,512
You want to see sin
of the wickedest kind? Here it is

898
01:31:13,600 --> 01:31:18,071
You want to see virtue left behind?
Here it is

899
01:31:18,160 --> 01:31:20,390
Sodom was vice and vice a versa

900
01:31:20,480 --> 01:31:24,189
You want to see where
the vice is worser? Here it is

901
01:31:24,280 --> 01:31:26,510
I mean, here it is

902
01:31:26,600 --> 01:31:31,469
You want to live life
in the rottenest way? Here it is

903
01:31:31,560 --> 01:31:35,872
Women and whisky night and day
Here it is

904
01:31:35,960 --> 01:31:40,431
You want to embrace the golden calf
Ankle and thigh and upper half?

905
01:31:40,520 --> 01:31:44,593
Here it is
I mean, here it is

906
01:31:44,680 --> 01:31:49,435
No Name City, No Name City
The Lord don't like it here

907
01:31:49,520 --> 01:31:53,877
No Name City, No Name City
Your reckonin' day is near

908
01:31:53,960 --> 01:31:57,919
No Name City, No Name City
Here's what he's gonna do

909
01:31:58,000 --> 01:32:02,471
Gobble up this town
Swallow it down and goodbye to you

910
01:32:02,560 --> 01:32:06,872
Will you go to heaven?
Will you go to hell?

911
01:32:06,960 --> 01:32:11,556
Either repent or fare thee well

912
01:32:11,640 --> 01:32:14,154
God'll take care o' No Name City

913
01:32:14,240 --> 01:32:16,435
Comes the end
and it won't be pretty

914
01:32:16,520 --> 01:32:20,877
Here it is
I mean, here it is

915
01:32:35,000 --> 01:32:40,757
Amen

916
01:32:58,120 --> 01:33:02,113
- Evening, Pardner.
- Evening, Elizabeth.

917
01:33:02,200 --> 01:33:05,715
- Evening, Ben.
- Evening, Elizabeth.

918
01:33:31,240 --> 01:33:34,073
I hear George Lonergan
pulled out today.

919
01:33:34,160 --> 01:33:37,277
- He's smart.
- He's broke.

920
01:33:37,360 --> 01:33:41,478
Ben thinks placer mining's
all but finished in these parts.

921
01:33:44,200 --> 01:33:45,838
What are we gonna do?

922
01:33:45,920 --> 01:33:48,354
I hear talk of a strike
up to Red Dog.

923
01:33:48,440 --> 01:33:53,878
- I'm not leaving my home, Ben.
- I wasn't suggesting it.

924
01:33:55,280 --> 01:33:59,034
I'll live on grass and mud water
before I'd do that.

925
01:33:59,120 --> 01:34:02,157
Ben isn't asking you
to leave your home.

926
01:34:02,240 --> 01:34:07,394
Damn it! Why not? You like this town
as much as I like Schermerhorn!

927
01:34:07,480 --> 01:34:10,552
That's right,
I hate what this town has become,

928
01:34:10,640 --> 01:34:13,108
but it's one place
we can live together.

929
01:34:14,720 --> 01:34:17,393
And there's nothing I hate as much

930
01:34:17,480 --> 01:34:21,359
as I love the two of you
and this cabin.

931
01:34:22,200 --> 01:34:27,274
If you want to go to Red Dog,
you go ahead, but I'm staying here.

932
01:34:27,360 --> 01:34:29,351
You come back whenever you want to.

933
01:34:30,720 --> 01:34:34,508
The only thing stopping you
being perfect is your stubbornness.

934
01:34:34,600 --> 01:34:38,798
Somebody should hit you till it's
gone. Somebody's gotta support us.

935
01:34:38,880 --> 01:34:41,474
You can't go through
a whole winter here alone.

936
01:34:41,560 --> 01:34:43,710
I won't leave her here alone.

937
01:34:44,800 --> 01:34:49,715
You'd let this man who took care
of you and nursed you back to health

938
01:34:49,800 --> 01:34:54,396
light out alone while you sleep
through winter like a fat groundhog?

939
01:34:54,480 --> 01:34:58,996
- If he goes, you go.
- And I ain't going.

940
01:35:00,800 --> 01:35:05,669
- Well, I'll go, then.
- If he goes, you go with him.

941
01:35:05,760 --> 01:35:09,799
Didn't I just tell you you can't go
through a winter alone here?

942
01:35:11,320 --> 01:35:13,515
You ever see such a stubborn woman?

943
01:35:14,600 --> 01:35:17,114
No, I never did.

944
01:35:17,760 --> 01:35:21,799
But if you ever hit her, you'll
have to deal with me straightaway.

945
01:35:44,800 --> 01:35:50,272
- I sure am one tired man tonight.
- Must be from lifting those cards.

946
01:35:52,000 --> 01:35:57,074
I only played a few hands last night.
I had a lucky streak. I broke even.

947
01:36:01,080 --> 01:36:04,436
You'll tell Three-Fingered Sweeney
I'll pay him next week.

948
